{"parentUuid":"aa9f413d-e42a-4814-b64b-f7f204ee35d7","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"9e7720b3-327b-4c3b-b049-d897bbc5f090","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"Query locks for usercodes and return only unmanaged ones. Why do we have to prefilter?"},"uuid":"847f00c2-b569-4468-82a1-063ff0ec284b","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:11:07.714Z","permissionMode":"bypassPermissions","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/raman/projects/lock_code_manager","sessionId":"3f097ff1-5bb6-4622-8cfe-35782dd270ba","version":"2.1.81","gitBranch":"feat/lock-reset-step","slug":"jolly-wandering-moonbeam"}
{"parentUuid":"847f00c2-b569-4468-82a1-063ff0ec284b","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01GFGg6yqiDp2XyL44oKR3Hx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nYou're right — the filtering should happen in `_async_get_unmanaged_codes`, not in `_async_check_existing_usercodes`. The inner function should just query the lock and return everything. The caller decides what's unmanaged.\n\nThat makes `_async_check_existing_usercodes` reusable for the options flow too, where the definition of \"unmanaged\" would be different (based on the new config being submitted)."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":207,"cache_read_input_tokens":411616,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":207},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CZjewxVEyMFv2yeLcsq3C","type":"assistant","uuid":"768f250e-720a-47dd-b9bb-a6cc8451a79a","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:11:21.215Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/raman/projects/lock_code_manager","sessionId":"3f097ff1-5bb6-4622-8cfe-35782dd270ba","version":"2.1.81","gitBranch":"feat/lock-reset-step","slug":"jolly-wandering-moonbeam"}
