{"parentUuid":"33bb98a7-a75d-4265-9a11-079402a1335c","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"0bc1d091-087f-4aef-af66-cf4ee14955c8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"I keep getting failed to call OTBR API"},"uuid":"422512df-0d8f-477d-8b4d-001046283ebb","timestamp":"2026-04-06T20:30:16.466Z","permissionMode":"bypassPermissions","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/raman/projects/lock_code_manager","sessionId":"3f097ff1-5bb6-4622-8cfe-35782dd270ba","version":"2.1.81","gitBranch":"main","slug":"jolly-wandering-moonbeam"}
{"parentUuid":"422512df-0d8f-477d-8b4d-001046283ebb","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014kW98nGfcEgMoDv7w6bt1T","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nThat's a different issue. The OTBR REST API isn't reachable from wherever you're trying to call it. A few things:\n\n**1. From the Thread integration UI:**\nHA → Settings → Integrations → Thread → click your border router → are you trying to use the \"Reset network\" / \"Form new network\" buttons there?\n\nIf so, the HA Thread integration is trying to reach `http://core-openthread-border-router:8081` (the URL from your earlier dataset). That hostname only resolves inside the supervisor network, so HA Core needs to be able to reach the add-on container.\n\n**Try:**\n- Settings → Add-ons → OpenThread Border Router → restart it\n- Then reload the Thread integration (3 dots → Reload)\n\n**2. Via the OTBR add-on web UI directly:**\nThe add-on logs that the web UI is on port 8081. Try opening it in a browser: `http://<your-ha-ip>:8081`\n\nIf the add-on doesn't have port 8081 exposed in its config, you won't be able to reach it from your browser. Check:\n- Settings → Add-ons → OpenThread Border Router → Configuration\n- Look for a \"Network\" section to expose port 8081\n\n**3. The simpler workaround: change channel via re-forming**\n\nSince the API is acting up, easier path:\n1. Stop the OTBR add-on\n2. Delete the Thread network from HA (Settings → Integrations → Thread → border router → 3 dots → Delete)\n3. Start the OTBR add-on\n4. It should form a new network — but the channel selection is automatic and may pick 15 again\n\n**4. The actually simpler workaround: physical move + restart**\n\nHonestly, before fighting the API, just try:\n1. Move the ZBT-2 stick a few feet away from your WiFi router\n2. Restart the OTBR add-on\n3. See if `ChannelAccessFailure` warnings go away in the new logs\n\nIf they do, channel 15 is fine and you just had RF proximity interference. Then try commissioning the lock again."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":6,"cache_creation_input_tokens":739,"cache_read_input_tokens":651846,"output_tokens":664,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":739,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CZo9ivD6UbmLrJzCAM12k","type":"assistant","uuid":"12aa1002-8901-4ba4-a486-a04b5ecd7924","timestamp":"2026-04-06T20:30:35.977Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/raman/projects/lock_code_manager","sessionId":"3f097ff1-5bb6-4622-8cfe-35782dd270ba","version":"2.1.81","gitBranch":"main","slug":"jolly-wandering-moonbeam"}
