{"parentUuid":"e67e65f7-bd93-45aa-be3a-88cd47bbaa58","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"f2ba0793-be79-4074-96c0-4a34eaf8ebff","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01J6CYYLmuY1hiextfw2NLoP","type":"tool_result","content":"# The Brands Proxy API\n\n## What It Is\n\nThe brands proxy API serves brand images (icons and logos) through Home Assistant's local API rather than directly from a CDN. It provides two endpoints:\n\n- `/api/brands/integration/{domain}/{image}` for integration branding\n- `/api/brands/hardware/{category}/{image}` for hardware images\n\nImages are cached locally and remain accessible during internet outages using a stale-while-revalidate strategy.\n\n## How Custom Integrations Use It\n\nStarting with Home Assistant 2026.3, developers can place brand assets directly in their integration. As stated in the documentation, \"just drop your images in a `brand/` folder and they show up in the UI.\"\n\nThe supported filenames include `icon.png`, `logo.png`, and their dark/high-resolution variants (`dark_icon.png`, `icon@2x.png`, etc.).\n\n## Manifest Changes\n\nThe provided content contains no information about manifest modifications. The documentation focuses on file structure rather than manifest configuration requirements for implementing local brand images.\n\n## Frontend Integration\n\nDevelopers using custom cards should leverage existing helpers: \"the `brandsUrl()` and `hardwareBrandsUrl()` helpers in `src/util/brands-url.ts` now return local API paths instead of CDN URLs.\""}]},"uuid":"8c18ed1a-11f6-4ffe-9498-e779e8beefbf","timestamp":"2026-04-07T19:42:02.962Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":4458,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# The Brands Proxy API\n\n## What It Is\n\nThe brands proxy API serves brand images (icons and logos) through Home Assistant's local API rather than directly from a CDN. It provides two endpoints:\n\n- `/api/brands/integration/{domain}/{image}` for integration branding\n- `/api/brands/hardware/{category}/{image}` for hardware images\n\nImages are cached locally and remain accessible during internet outages using a stale-while-revalidate strategy.\n\n## How Custom Integrations Use It\n\nStarting with Home Assistant 2026.3, developers can place brand assets directly in their integration. As stated in the documentation, \"just drop your images in a `brand/` folder and they show up in the UI.\"\n\nThe supported filenames include `icon.png`, `logo.png`, and their dark/high-resolution variants (`dark_icon.png`, `icon@2x.png`, etc.).\n\n## Manifest Changes\n\nThe provided content contains no information about manifest modifications. The documentation focuses on file structure rather than manifest configuration requirements for implementing local brand images.\n\n## Frontend Integration\n\nDevelopers using custom cards should leverage existing helpers: \"the `brandsUrl()` and `hardwareBrandsUrl()` helpers in `src/util/brands-url.ts` now return local API paths instead of CDN URLs.\"","durationMs":2843,"url":"https://developers.home-assistant.io/blog/2026/02/24/brands-proxy-api/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"e67e65f7-bd93-45aa-be3a-88cd47bbaa58","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/raman/projects/lock_code_manager","sessionId":"3f097ff1-5bb6-4622-8cfe-35782dd270ba","version":"2.1.81","gitBranch":"main","slug":"jolly-wandering-moonbeam"}
